commentBody:
@Maverator 

It's really not fair to compare a constructed-into-the-real-world puzzle with a twist, to the Platonic ideal of Puzzle that incorporates a myriad of twists in the twists in the twists.

It was a good puzzle.  The fact that I can imagine something even more wonderful is meaningless, because *I haven't constructed that puzzle*.

@Steve L 

It is so rare I can provide you with some new knowledge - rather than the other way round -that I'll jump at the chance. In Polish it's IMPAS 🙂

I only know IMPASSE as the English spelling though.

@Steve L 

Thank you for this very detailed and very clear explanation.

I don't follow football, but I could actually see it in my mind's eye!

@Hardroch 

Nice!  Thanks for the link.

So, like an unprotected lone fawn in the middle of a field sits my very short comment.  Is there an emu in the bushes ready to pounce?  Hopefully this collection of words will provide some protection.

@Mavis 

Yeah, I'm pretty certain you could get a *lot* or responses to that one.

There are some extremely clever people posting here, as I'm beginning to appreciate.

@Eli 

The reason crossword puzzles use the year a movie was released is because that’s what AMPAS dies (despite some confusing information on their website).

Movies released in 2024 will be eligible for Oscars awarded in 2025. And each of those Oscars will have the year 2024 engraved on them.

@Patrick 

I don't really know if it's a violation of the "rule".

But I *do* know that that's not a rule.

@Francis 

One of the more experienced solvers will hopefully chime in, but I am pretty sure that it *is* a rule that the clue can't (shouldn't?) include a word that is also found in the answer.

Patrick, that also jumped out at me.

@Francis 

I'd prefer not argue at all.

But since you rather emphatically claimed to know that it isn't a rule, I chimed in.

@Andrzej 

Look at you and the baseball idioms!

Next thing you know, you're going to be explaining the infield fly rule to all of us.

@B

Actually, what is more interesting is the fact that often people in these comments are suprised somebody liked (or disliked) something they themselves disliked (or liked). Personal preferences and personal experiences are just that, personal, and we have different ones, obviously. That favorite Jesse Goldberg puzzle of yours was one of my least enjoyable this year. Go figure!

The cool thing is though that neither you nor me are wrong about how we feel about any puzzle.

@Nancy J. 

Comment of the year 🤩









[Moderation evasion space]

@Nancy J. 
And here I thought you always enjoyed my Thursday specials:-(





Roast breast of emu, à la sauce Rébus.

@Nancy J. - While I agree with the spirit of your analogy, I do understand why people get grouchy.  Your analogy would advise that those who know they won't like the Thursday puzzle should just skip it instead of doing it and getting mad about it (e.g. why go to the restaurant on Thursday?!)

But the true analogy is that you purchased a special meal plan with the restaurant to serve you dinner every night of the week and you are continually annoyed with the Thursday menu.  If you buy the subscription for NYT Games, you expect to be able to play them every day... it's not like you get to choose 1 day each week to complete the puzzle and these poor souls keep trying the Thursday hoping it will be different.

Should the same cast of characters complain and moan about Thursday knowing that Thursday is purpose-built to be different?  Probably not, but "just skip it" isn't really a fair retort either... especially in a world where NYTs and literally everthing else in our lives is gamified and people like to maintain a streak.

@Nancy J.

These types of comments make me sad, since all it really does is further entrench people into separate camps. Sure complaints can be mean spirited and overwhelming at times but is mocking Thursday complainers really solving anything? Are you winning anyone over to trying out rebus puzzles by insulting them? If anything you're just proving to them that you *are* smug and elitist.

It's not on you to convince others but contributing to the problem isn't helping either.

@B 

My gym has a sign on the front counter offering a free T-shirt for a 5 star review on Google.  I told them that was unethical, but it's still there months later.  Sigh...  It's a shame that resources like that are so easily corrupted.  I tried to notify Google but wasn't sure how and gave up.  You reminded me to try again.

Is the Christopher Kimball thing good, bad or neutral?  I don't know how to take it.  He can be very annoying at times..........  I try not to be.

@Nancy J.

Yeah, being kind to one another goes a long way. We can't control how other people act but we can control how we respond to them. 

The regulars here play a large role in shaping the community since people will follow their lead. If they're kindly responding to angry comments and being helpful, people will perceive this place as a friendly one and imitate them. If they're the ones who are snidely criticizing others and clapping back in the comments, people will perceive this place to be a toxic one and act accordingly.

@Lewis 

It's hard to be sure, but one suspects that answers to the first and second questions are likely to involve alcohol intake....   (juuuust kidding!)

(I tried to check his picture, but it's just an AVATAR/robot.)

@B 

You really touched a nerve with that old saw "If one can't do, teach."

As a former teacher, I submit that teaching *is* doing something, something that is a talent and a skill and a service, ushering new brains and new thought into a discipline.

@Grant 
Same here for PANACEA. 
I'm however unknowledgeable about Hello Kitty so I put WHISKER - that one didn't last long!.

@B 
Perhaps it is the settings on my PC screen, but blue+gray is so similar to just-plain-blue that I can't easily tell the difference. OF COURSE, I can click off onto another cell to see the grayed cells, but as I have the retention span of a chipmunk, by the time I click back, I've forgotten where they are.


Emus never forget.

@Byro

Thanks all. 

It appears I dele-ed my N myself.

@MExpat @MExpat On your 2 points: 

I don't think anyone's claiming this is anything but a crossword. Yet, being a word puzzle, answers should be justified. There are 5 answers here that are completely unjustified. Can I go about my day unphased after completing this puzzle? Sure. Do I need spiritual inspiration from crosswords? Not really. Do I expect more refinement from one of the most visible crossword publishers in the world? Absolutely. 

I know many, many American football fans that would take major issue with you claiming their sport isn't meaningful haha

@Jairus I think you may be expecting too much from this type of  conceit. Yes, it would be nice for the unclued answers in the puzzle to also be thematic, but for this particular kind of gimmick (needing to reverse the letters in two sections of an answer), it would be impossible to find enough candidates for them to also all be thematic. 

You may think that means it shouldn’t be published, but the “theme” that the unclued answers in this puzzle follow is that they are all valid crossword entries instead of being gobbledygook. That is a difficult enough feat of construction that it should be admired in its own right, and IMO makes for an excellent and NYT-worthy puzzle.

In some other similar cases, solvers have suggested maybe hinting at both answers in the clue. Like, for example: “Wonder drug created by a Disney villain” or “Disney villain discovers a wonder drug”, but whether that’s better or worse is a matter of taste.

@George 

I’ve probably solved 10 years’ worth of NYT puzzles and still find some of the themes/tricks frustrating. But I enjoy the novel gimmicks that constructors come up with. 

Good luck with your future puzzle solving! And try ditching the Google; it’s much more rewarding to figure it out on your own.

@A 

Thanx. 
Academically I was a late bloomer so I couldn't have qualified for AP as an HS student back in the late  fifties. If we even had such an option back then.

@Erin 

Oh jeez. I didn't even notice.

I was too busy thinking about the name Henrietta and what it meant.

@Bonnie Ann 

A great taco salad and lively conversation with family and friends did the trick. I finished the puzzle. It wasn't that bad once I looked at it in the whole. I had figured out what I could and got help from the wordplay column.  I didn't have that sense of fun and satisfaction others have had solving this one. We all have different pleasurable solves which is no reflection on the constructor or the solver. 

Thank you Jesse Guzman for a very interesting Thursday game! You had an outstanding NYT debut. Cheers y'all.

@Linda Jo 

Sending good thoughts your way.

Please take care!

@sotto voce 

Yeah. That happens to me in Octordle when I have most of the letters and it looks like the word b/4 I unscramble it.  We really want chaos to make sense.

I often think about the blind spot where the optic nerve goes through the retina, but the brain kindly fills in the gap for you so you don’t perceive missing light reception.  What else am I “sensing” that my brain is actually filling-in for me?

@Joel 

I'm not sure what you're on about there with IMPASSE [Intractable situation].  That's how it's spelled (or spelt) here, and I have never seen any indication that it's spelled differently in any other country.



